Make the save-slot filename writable

SaveGameState and LoadGameState build the save filename by overwriting one
character of a string in place:

    static char *filename = FILENAME_BASE ".SV ";
    ...
    *(filename + SAVE_SLOT_INDEX) = slot_char;

filename points at a string literal. On DOS, in real mode with no memory
protection, a literal was writable, so stamping the slot digit over the
trailing space worked and cost nothing. Compiled natively the literal lives in
read-only memory, and that write is a fault.

It faulted the instant a level started: InitializeLevel calls
SaveGameState('T') to record the checkpoint a death restarts from, so the first
thing a new game did was write to the literal and die -- which looked from the
outside like the game crashing right after Begin. Nothing before a started
level touched it, which is why the menus were fine and only playing was not.

Declaring filename as an array rather than a pointer gives each function its
own writable copy of the same bytes, so the in-place edit lands where it is
allowed to. The initializer, its length, and every later use are unchanged.

diff --git a/game1.c b/game1.c
index 027948d..5c974bd 100644
--- a/game1.c
+++ b/game1.c
@@ -9322,7 +9322,7 @@ capable of exiting the game if a manipulated save file is loaded.
 */
 bbool LoadGameState(char slot_char)
 {
-    static char *filename = FILENAME_BASE ".SV ";
+    static char filename[] = FILENAME_BASE ".SV ";
     FILE *fp;
     int checksum;
 
@@ -9364,7 +9364,7 @@ character, '1' through '9', or the letter 'T' for the temporary save file.
 */
 static void SaveGameState(char slot_char)
 {
-    static char *filename = FILENAME_BASE ".SV ";
+    static char filename[] = FILENAME_BASE ".SV ";
     FILE *fp;
     word checksum;
 
